definition: "Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is an 84-amino-acid peptide hormone secreted by the four parathyroid glands — small glands embedded in the posterior surface of the thyroid. PTH is the primary hormonal regulator of calcium and phosphorus homeostasis, operating through three principal mechanisms: (1) bone resorption — PTH activates osteoclasts, which break down bone matrix to release calcium and phosphorus into the bloodstream; (2) renal calcium reabsorption — PTH increases calcium reabsorption in the renal tubules, reducing urinary calcium loss; and (3) vitamin D activation — PTH stimulates the kidneys to convert 25-hydroxyvitamin D (the storage form) to 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D (calcitriol, the active form), which increases intestinal calcium absorption. PTH secretion is exquisitely sensitive to serum calcium: low calcium stimulates PTH release within seconds; high calcium suppresses it. The standard blood test measures 'intact PTH' — the full 84-amino-acid molecule — which is the biologically active, clinically relevant form."
why_it_matters: "PTH is rarely included in standard blood panels, yet it provides critical context for interpreting calcium and vitamin D results — and identifies two of the most common and underdiagnosed endocrine conditions. The first is primary hyperparathyroidism (covered in the calcium page): a parathyroid adenoma secreting excess PTH regardless of calcium levels, producing persistent hypercalcemia and bone depletion. PTH measurement immediately confirms this diagnosis when calcium is elevated. The second, and far more common, is secondary hyperparathyroidism from vitamin D deficiency — the most prevalent hormone deficiency in the Western world. When vitamin D is deficient, intestinal calcium absorption falls, serum calcium drops slightly, and PTH rises compensatorily. This elevated PTH drives continuous bone resorption to maintain normal serum calcium — the body dissolves bone to keep blood calcium stable. Serum calcium remains normal (making the deficiency invisible without PTH measurement), but bone density is being depleted. This silent bone loss — occurring in millions of people with vitamin D deficiency who have 'normal' calcium — is caught by testing PTH alongside calcium and vitamin D."

